e bead, especially in mid-air or under layer shear. These will either curl up during printing, snap off during support removal, or buckle when you lift the part.\n\n**Second failure point:** The **444 overhang faces** beyond 45°. On a spiral stair, these are the underside of each step and possibly the risers. Without aggressive supports, those unsupported tread tips will droop, string, or detach from the build plate entirely — especially toward the top of the 53.5 mm height, where layer cooling is less effective.\n\n**Specific warp location**: The outermost tips of the highest stair treads. They have thin cross-section, long unsupported span, and they're farthest from the model's base. In PLA, they'll curl upward at the trailing edge. I...[truncated]"},"logprobs":null,"finish_reason":"stop"}],"usage":{"prompt_tokens":"[REDACTED]","completion_tokens":"[REDACTED]","total_tokens":"[REDACTED]","prompt_tokens_details":"[REDACTED]","prompt_cache_hit_tokens":"[REDACTED]","prompt_cache_miss_tokens":"[REDACTED]"},"system_fingerprint":"fp_8b330d02d0_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402"}},"duration":2111,"error":null}
